Tl;dr- when trying to fix systematic problems in grad school, don't throw people who are trying to find their balance to maintain their mental health under the bus, thanks.
(For the record, I plan on taking this weekend off to do work around the house and play DnD, so it's not like I don't ever take breaks.)
I feel bad when I don't follow my work schedule. Making me feel guilty for following it too is pretty shitty, especially since it's tied up in somewhat sensitive issues for me.
Maintaining work-life balance is an important conversation for us to have in grad school.But adding more prescriptivism to how a "good" grad student should work is not the way to solve it
People work differently. Sometimes their schedules are determined by family stuff, sometimes by health, sometimes by other things. Frankly, the reasons why are no one's business but theirs.
So for me, my work schedule is very tied up in maintaining my mental health. It's what works for me.So telling me that taking care of myself makes other people look bad is...yikes.

So in summary, this study provided very valuable insight into the genes that might be important in PC risk assessment. However, more work (mainly via case-control studies) is still needed to determine if the additional genes are indeed PC predisposition genes #ProstateJC7/7

Finally, this study evaluated a very selected cohort of PC patients who were thought to have a higher likelihood of having an underlying inherited risk for PC (hence the genetic testing), thus it is difficult to generalize these findings to all PC patients.#ProstateJC6/7

and although there were some comparative analyses of total mutational frequency in this cohort vs. gnomad, differences in sequencing, QC metrics, germline calling algorithms, and ancestry assignment between both groups makes it hard to draw any solid conclusions#ProstateJC5/7

First, as the authors correctly indicated, this is a cross-sectional observational study that looked at the frequency of the pathogenic alterations in PC but did not examine matched controls to evaluate mutational enrichment in these genes compared with the general population4/7

Although this study is  very informative for the ongoing discussion of the missing heritability of PC,the clinical utility of germline testing in these patients, and the additional diagnostic yield of expanded germline testing, a few things should be kept in mind:#ProstateJC3/7

This study identified a surprisingly high frequency of pathogenic germline mutations in several cancer predisposition genes, many of which have not been linked to a higher risk of PC and are not part of the NCCN recommendations for germline genetic testing#ProstateJC2/7 https://t.co/pGbMunfWjE

In this model we can alter one property whilst keeping others constant. ‚ÄúRoughening‚Äù the surface in this model has the sane effect (freakily similar pressure-volume loop summaries) as the observational data

There is though always a nagging question of the alchemy of statistics on observational data drawing a simple conclusion from a complex system and this is where have a ground up haemodynamic physical model in a computer really complements the genetic data
Of course there are assumptions and subtle gotchas which is why best practice is to have >1 meta analysis techniques (we used 3; all consistent)
This means we can get arguably better-than-knockouts style X causes Y from at scale genetics and physiology from *observational* data. It‚Äôs almost like magic!

The multi-snp Mendelian Randomisation (MR) techniques can in effect isolate the physiology one is interested in despite the hideously complex ‚Äútouch one thing and 100s of downstream things change‚Äù (in formal terms; handling pleitotropy)

On a broader scale I‚Äôm also excited to see physiology being rebooted with this combination of at scale, carefully measured physiological phenotypes (@uk_biobank, take a bow) and Mendelian randomisation techniques (@mendel_random - a remarkable insight into how to use genetics)
It‚Äôs been a real ‚Äúteam science‚Äù paper - none of the labs could have done this alone, and we all learned a lot from the other groups - hearts - they are ... pretty complex organs !

The triangulation of evidence (hat tip to @MarcusMunafo) is, in our opinion, strong and robust evidence that the cardiac trabeculation first observed by Leonardo da Vinci is a key functional part of delivering efficient human heart physiology

Finally @HannahVMeyer in my group used a variety of Mendelian Randomisation techniques to use our discovered genetic loci as unbiased statistical instruments strongly supporting increase of trabeculation leads to improved cardiac output (and change in QRS duration)

In a first principle haemodynamic model Marta Serrani from Maria Constantino‚Äôs group showed that increasing the roughness of the internal surface of the heart in their model non intuitively increased cardiac output

This was in @uk_biobank‚Äôs awesome MRI imaging resource ‚Äúonly‚Äù 18,000 people from which @timdawes2 in @DrDeclanORegan‚Äôs group could derive the first large scale pressure-volume loop characterisation of cardiac output and observe a kink between trabeculae level and cardiac output

We brought our different techniques to bear on this, developing a novel image based measurement for this surface (inspired by the fractal description of coastlines), finding genetic loci that underlie the phenomenon (and replicating the finding) >>

This has been a great collaboration between @DrDeclanORegan‚Äôs imaging and physiology lab, @stuartacook1‚Äôs cardiology lab, Maria Constantino‚Äôs biological fluid dynamics lab and my own genomics lab

So - it‚Äôs a long journey here - but GWAS scientists -I propose we change the root term to ‚Äúwe took the a subset of people from our study population which where the approximation of a well mixed population was reasonable and deviations well handled with genotype PCs‚Äù
This then, you might say lazily but more like unknowingly, propagates through all the downstream comms with an implicit reinforcement that ‚Äú European‚Äù is a well defined scientific thing.

Because it‚Äôs long winded to say ‚Äúour modelled population is predominantly self identified as European but clearly excludes some well known population structure in Europe, such as Finns and Sardianians and some other people were not sure about‚Äù we go for ‚ÄúEuropean‚Äù

When we do GWAS we‚Äôre not trying to reconstruct human population history nor match up cultural and complex ‚Äòethnicity‚Äô labels. We just want ... as close as we can get to a randomly mating population and then we throw in 40 PCs and - if we‚Äôre pedantic - say our QQ plots are good
This is not only Finns; Sardinia needs to be excluded as well, and probably other groups I don‚Äôt know about at all :)
(Most of the Finnish geneticist I know are quietly proud of this and mutter things like Sisu here)

This is mainly due to clear substructure in commonly accepted ethnicities, eg ‚ÄúEuropean‚Äù ethnicity includes Finns whereas for a geneticist its a bit of a disaster to think Finns can be well modelled with PCs in a big ‚ÄúEuropean‚Äù bag
Secondly is that even the 1000G ‚Äúlabelled people‚Äù don‚Äôt all go to that spot and certainly not any self identified label (eg ‚Äúethnicity‚Äù)

Why? Well first off what we are really trying to do is say ‚Äúthis group of people can be well modelled as a well mixed, randomly mating group if I throw in 40 odd principle components‚Äù and actually should be paired with a QQ plot (ideally on a random phenotype) to prove it

Whilst in population genetics rant mode, I really think we need a different word than population (or population labels like ‚ÄúEuropean‚Äù) for the GWAS trick of taking the group of people in the densest spot of a PC1+PC2 plot with 1000G overlay and using its label

He left us three years ago on February 11th. He is loved and he is missed.https://t.co/9dfjRFc8n0

I remember my grandfather, Peter Lorillard Tailer, as a brilliant, adventurous, loving, and gentle man. He was the world's best bedtime storyteller, perhaps the reason I have always dreamt so vividly. His impact on me and on this world was precious and it was powerful. https://t.co/YIT4mPh3Aw

By the time I became interested in physics & engineering, ~senior year of high school/ early college, his tinkering had slowed down quite a bit. To this day I don't possess the knowledge to really understand the science behind his work. I wish we could have chatted about it more.
For most of this work I was either not yet born or a very small child. The above information I learned entirely from family members or searching on google.
That year he also filed a patent application for his invention, "Thermal Lag Engine," and was granted it in 1995.https://t.co/XUqgyi0gTp https://t.co/CgXE7NoA3A
He presented this work at the 1993 Intersociety Energy Conversion Engineering Conference with an abstract titled "External combustion Otto cycle thermal lag engine."https://t.co/QasPcYa6vA

He wasn't just tinkering for fun, though. He had simplified the design & improved the efficiency of the Stirling by exploiting the machine's thermal lag, the lag time created by the internal fluid‚Äôs thermal inertia, with a single moving part and a greater transfer of energy.
My grandparent's left Windfarm in 1992 and moved to a retirement community in New Hampshire where my grandfather continued his physics and engineering hobby in their apartment.

In 1990 he was profiled as an amateur scientist in Scientific American for his backyard version of the Stirling machine that he built with coffee and soda cans.https://t.co/MfaovcOqlv https://t.co/oWLBIjumvb

In 1989 he published an article about Stirling machines in the journal Energy Exploration & Exploitation.https://t.co/57RYEq9aJk(side note: if anyone has access to this PDF please hook me up!!) https://t.co/hw336znngM

A Stirling engine is a "closed-cycle regenerative heat engine" - basically a more efficient version of a steam engine that has a sealed cylinder, thus harnessing the energy that would otherwise be lost in the form of steam.https://t.co/yDpI5uClmR https://t.co/Q1rGSAalt9

My grandfather was a retired patent lawyer and a hobby engineer. He was interested in renewable energy sources and efficient machines. In addition to windmills and water pumps, he fiddled around with Stirling engines.

Interested in using pext? The easiest way to get started is to check out your favorite gene in the fancy new update to the gnomAD browser, which now shows pext across all tissues (thanks to Nick Watts). https://t.co/HIuDeVZ4tP

It also improves gene discovery exercises in severe diseases like developmental delay and autism, by making it possible to remove a subset of LoF variants that are weakly expressed and have no disease signal, and flagging highly expressed regions with larger effects. https://t.co/k3rxuJrZ2m

The final metric was called (after some agonizing) the proportion of expressed transcripts or pext score. And it turns out to be broadly useful in separating important bits of genes from unimportant ones - e.g. throwing out lots of common LoFs but few ClinVar variants. https://t.co/xWiTFwPSIP

So @beryl_bbc devised a systematic approach to annotate variants based on the expression of the affected exon across GTEx tissues, accounting for various biases in short-read data. The basic strategy is summarized in this figure: https://t.co/8Cq64D55Ow

Our team manually curated 401 of these variants, and found (as expected) a ton of errors. One of the major error types was what we called a "transcript error", meaning the variant fell on a transcript that looked like it wasn't real, or was very weakly expressed.

Our latest preprint, led by @beryl_bbc, starts with a mystery: why are there hundreds of people in gnomAD who shouldn't be there? These people carry predicted truncating variants in genes where these are known to cause severe dominant pediatric disease. https://t.co/lb6eTeWneT

If you buy all this ... does this means genetics solves it all? Absolutely not! For starters this "thicket of molecular and cell biology" is basically... understanding life on a molecular scale. And, furthermore, one needs to take this insight into actually changing things

@GA4GH is working hard to make responsible data access worldwide a reality - responsible as in fitting into a framework from a UN human right - right to science - and being consistent with national and trans national legislation)

(The sheer logistics here are a bit eye watering; this means tracking all these people, sequencing their genome, collecting phenotypes and then responsibly sharing access to data to researchers. Thankfully @uk_biobank shows the logistics is doable >>

Is this feasible? Basically yes. There is already "in plans" of at least 5 million people around the world in cohorts and a likely another 5 million (at least) in clinical genomes which could be provided for secondary use for research

As diseases are often 1% or 0.5% of the population, this gets you into the millions of people, and the most useful variants (homozygous loss of function) are also the rarest; hence 10s of millions in a virtual cohort

An interesting question is how many people do you need? This is hard to answer, and like all statistical problems, more observations (people) is *always* good. But the sense is that things start working when one has 10,000 odd cases of a phenotype ("disease")

(Some will be easier because the frequency of 'interesting' changes are higher in the population studied. Most of the time though things will be easier or harder due to this thicket of molecular and cell biology- sometimes it will drop out, sometimes it is really head scratching)

Does this work? Absolutely! We have excellent worked out cases from specific disease cohorts (Type II diabetes and Crohn's disease are two leading cases). There is no reason this should not work on basically *everything*, though for sure somethings will be easier than others

However these loss of function alleles are not the only interesting changes. It is also useful to look at weaker changes or changes which only alter one aspect of the protein. In a "traditional" model organism one would call this 'an allelic series'.

(This is why populations with a tradition of consanguineous marriages are interesting, such as Born in Bradford or East London Genes and Health, or Qatar, as one gets a far higher rate of homozygous alleles)

And innovative payers (both newcos and existing giants) should make this an easy-to-access benefit. There‚Äôs no ‚Äòbenefit‚Äô in being willing to pay for medical care that patients can‚Äôt even access! (12/12)
Providers will increasingly pay for transport themselves in a value-based reimbursement ecosystem (11/n)

The challenge is how to pay for it. Stating the obvious, but the cost of an unnecessary hospital admission or avoidable clinical complication is typically 100-1000x the cost of medical transport. This should be a no-brainer for anyone incented to lower total cost of care (10/n)

Many organizations working on this need in both traditional and disruptive ways: @circulation @roundtriphealth @kid1transport @Medlert @AAMS. Think ride sharing companies (eg @uberwellness4u) will make a huge impact (9/n)

Who is working to change this? Telemedicine and home-based care will solve some of the challenge, but in many instances patients still need diagnostics and treatment in a facility, like my patient did (8/n)

My mind explodes when I meet patients who have to make major choices like this based on the cost of getting around. And there are many more patients who are even more debilitated and need transport solutions even more badly than my patient (7/n)
By the time we see him, his troponin has normalized and repeat echo is normal. We suspect viral myocarditis (good prognosis). Ironically a lucky outcome (6/n)

That hospital recommends cardiac cath a few days later. But he starts feeling a little better, so he decides to go home (!!) via public bus (!!) and come back to the VA hospital on a weekday, when he can afford it. Thankfully he remains stable at home (5/n)

That hospital has none of his records, and he knows that care there isn‚Äôt ideal for him. But it‚Äôs cheaper to get there, so there‚Äôs that. Unfortunately, he might be pretty sick: he has an elevated troponin, and an echocardiogram shows new wall motion abnormalities (4/n)

A week ago he develops pleuritic chest pain at home. Calls the telehealth line, triage nurse says to come to the ED. The right advice. But it‚Äôs a weekend, and transport to the VA hospital costs $16 ($4 on weekdays). So he decides to take a bus to a different local hospital (3/n)

He has a chronic autoimmune disease and relies on a wheelchair to get around. A few years ago he nearly went bankrupt from ambulance bills, so lives in general fear of the cost associated with medical emergencies (2/n)
Thread: Why the transformation of medical transport could not come sooner.Recently admitted a 60 something old veteran to our hospital. His story is all too common (1/n)

So that's it, I feel this thread has been (more than) long enough as it is. But if you want to learn more here's a great review on inovirus biology https://t.co/1rCnkWlhVy , and here's the link again to our preprint on the "extended inovirus universe" \o/ https://t.co/kc45P7qyp6 https://t.co/QGdWGpI8Ff
And finally, they hold great promises for innovative applications, e.g. heat-resistant protein-based filament, vector for targeted delivery, etc..

If you are growing / working with a bacterial isolates, chances are it is infected by one (or multiple) inoviruses, which may significantly impact the cell phenotype (see e.g. this nice work in Neisseiria https://t.co/sIgo9x45SB)
So.. where do that leaves us.. My personal take is that inovirus prevalence, diversity, and impact on microbial communities has been vastly underestimated.

Third - when residing in a host cell, they can make it resistant to other (completely unrelated) viruses ! This was discovered by @AdairLBorges as part of a beautiful work looking at interactions between inoviruses, other viruse, and the host CRISPR-Cas system

Second - they are associated with virtually all bacteria groups, and surprisingly also some archaea (!!). That's where we teamed up with @reb_daly  and @TheWrightonLab to validate this experimentally, using a cultivated strain of these archaea

First - inoviruses are likely not a single family, but likely a full viral order divided into 6 families (figure network ?). Despite their short genome, they also encode also a very large diversity of gene (when considered collectively)
What can we learn from this extended collection ? A lot obviously, and probably some things that are still to be discovered.. but we focused on 3 main points

In this work, we show that the inoviruses were actually present in genomes and metagenomes from the beinning, we just weren't good at detecting them (see https://t.co/9Bz8zIj56X). And once we understood how to find them, we collected ~10k of these !

One thing that's always been weird though: while we were discovering (hundreds of) thousands of new viruses in metagenomes, inoviruses have so far been mostly absent from these dataset. So we are left with the ~ 50 known isolates.
Finally, the phage display technology is all based on inoviruses grown on E Coli, and leverage their filamentous virion and simple genome (see a nice explanation here -> https://t.co/e9k57o0Bkr)

Probably the most famous inovirus was found in vibrio cholerae, and this one was noteworthy because it actually encodes the cholera toxin ! So the phage is what makes you (indirectly) sick (although it still need the bacterial cell) https://t.co/Su9eA4jHBP

We can't really get rid of the earthworms, but we can take care to not spread them to new areas. If I were to move to property in northern Mn, this would mean not bringing any of these potted plants with me.

Earthworms eat and breakdown leaf litter. Woods in areas without them have much thicker layers of decaying leaves than areas that do have them. This thick leaf mulch is what many plants have adapted to. They dont do so well when earthworms are around.

Just found an earthworm exploring the surface in one of my overwintering pepper pots. In Mn, such earthworms are considered invasive.The glaciers had wiped them out in this area and the plants that followed when they retreated adapted to earthworms not being around. https://t.co/TDsTyRs607

10: reach out to your scientific society, they can help you get engaged
9: you don‚Äôt have to go at it alone. there are lots of people and organizations that can help you get started on the right track. also, tell a personal story and think about your own passion
8: reflect on how and where you feel most comfortable engaging
7: learn about new resources. have you heard of @DukeSciPol? üòâ
6: just get started!
5: listen first, and framing matters when you share your science. make sure you connect it to what the person or office cares about
4: reach out to congressional offices in your home district - staff are placed in those offices and you can engage with them. also, offices want to hear from their constituents (you!)
3: missed opportunity for folks to be involved at the local and state levels
2: recognize that science is a social enterprise, science and advocacy go hand in hand. public responds well to scientists sharing their expertise
1: co design your research studies with folks who will use it

If you are interested in Lactobacilli, cellulase, cojugation or pili, please have a look at the manuscript and feel free to provide feedback!

We were excited with these beautiful pictures and dug a little deeper in the genome. We now suspect that these pili are linked to conjugation genes, which we found to be coded on plasmids in two strains. Unfortunately, the detected plasmids were poorly characterized. https://t.co/WJSF8PYEvz

This led to the discovery of a putative cellulase gene in this species, which has never been found in lactic acid bacteria before!Furthermore, we took the effort to photograph all strains of this species using scanning electron microscopy, and detected the presence of pili.

We suspected these were members of the Lactobacillus mudanjiangensis species of which only one strain was isolated before. WGS of the type strain confirmed this. We could thus perform the first comparative genome analysis of this species! https://t.co/ja4Fm6fSM4

We isolated lots of bacteria from this project and performed whole genome sequencing (WGS) on a subset for further analysis. After phylogenetic tree construction, we found three strains that clearly belonged to the same species but were unrelated to any publicly available genome.

A few years ago we organized a citizen science project, @FermePekes, in which we asked participants to perform spontaneous carrot juice ü•ïfermentations at home. We found the ecosystem to be dominated by Lactobacilli.The study can be found here: https://t.co/aDLR4s8NpO https://t.co/qlYwx86YKo

A Finnish cop-drama I'm watching (called "Bordertown"; season 1, episode 7) just illustrated this terminal phase of a rabies infection very clearly. It wasn't a point of conversation by characters, but the writers for the show very clearly had researched the disease.

They'll talk & interact with family. Their seizures and other symptoms will diminish. This often gives the family feelings of hope, as their loved one has come back to them. But this phase is shortly followed by death.I haven't found any research that helps explain the pattern.

The classical presentation of the disease includes delirium and hydrophobia (the throat seizes painfully when the victim tries to drink).An aspect of the disease progression that is less well-known is that sometimes just before death the patient will return to lucidity.

Rabies is a terrifying disease. Without vaccination after exposure, the survival rate is very, very low once symptoms have started. Like on the order of single digits across all of human history. (With vaccination, the survival rate is very high.)

In some sense this is well understood by people who deliver this, but it is frustrating when institutions and funding agencies can't think outside the 'discovery scientist' - wrapped up in single PI, lack of team science, individual thinking.

We need to have a "track" - career path - for scientists and engineers who work in these science infrastructure components. This does happen in some places, but not enough, and there is no doubt that they can be inappropriate snobbery by the more "discovery focused" scientists

Pieces of infrastructure - databases, cohorts, large sample collections etc should be assessed by the science they enable - the papers that cite and use them, and the impact of the work done using them.

Consortium "authorship" on papers which *use* the results of the data (quite common in big cohort world) is bad in my view; this interaction is better represented by citing the main (primary) paper, and for the authors of the primary paper be able to show the impact of that

A view. Consortium authorship as the "front" author (single is best in my view) of the primary paper on a topic is good in my view. It succinctly represents everyone, removes (reduces) pointless arguments of listing order and shows a joint endeavour.

#WomenInScience are the only reason I have a chance at a life in STEM. I'm thankful, and I always want to be an ally.

2017 - Now: I get a chance to grow so much as a scientist under the mentorship of Dr. Rachel Schwartz (@rachelss). Dr. Schwartz's commitment to open science and inclusive teaching is what convinced the NSF that @universityofri was the right home for me for 2y.

2009 - 2017: Dr. Nicole Valenzuela stands by me through good and bad as we collaborate on my PhD research. She taught me about critically thinking about hypotheses, going out for personal funding, and how to dream big and boil it down into pubs.

2008: Dr. Pam Yelick at Tufts gave me a chance to work on dental pulp stem cells. Dr. Yelick taught me so much about doing sound research, cell culture, working with animals, and so much more. Further mentored by Dr. Weibo Zhang who gave me so much, not limited to patience.

2007: Graduate, no grad schools accepted me. Wrote an off the cuff email to Dr. Nicola Nelson (Victoria University of Wellington) and she gave me a chance to assist in tuatara research work for 3mo. in NZ. Worked in a wonderful lab with Drs. @DrReptilia, Kim Miller, Hilary Miller

I'm going to stop there. There's not much point in arguing against a group of people who want to introduce a species to New Zealand for plant control, when they haven't even established whether that species will actually control the plants.

"Little is known about the effect of root feeding by moth plant beetle on the fitness of moth plant in South America"Perhaps you should do some studies first to demonstrate that the moth plant beetle will actually kill the moth plant, *before* introducing it in NZ.

"Adults feed on moth plant foliage but this damage is not usually significant."... and this is the species you want to introduce to get rid of the moth plant - something that causes "not usually significant" damage?

"... without a full taxonomic revision or genetic study it is difficult to determine if the cupripennis complex represents a group of related species or a widespread, panmictic and highly variable species."Perhaps you should do those genetic studies on your collection.

"In 2010/11 moth plant beetles were collected from sites near Buenos Aires and La Plata and were identified in Argentina incorrectly (in Leschen 2018) as Colaspis argentinensis."And this time you're going to be *really careful* with collection, right?

"In Hamilton City, Waikato Regional Council also receives about 80 calls a year asking for advice on moth plant control."A bit over one call per week. If that's too much of an ordeal, perhaps you could print out fliers to refer people to this web page:https://t.co/F2vnLrKNOW

"Based on an average of 2 hours work for a Biosecurity Officer per site, there has been approximately 1400 hours spent on moth plant"Wow, that number's over 1000, sounds like a lot:"... which is 35 weeks... for the last 6 years"So... not even one person's worth for 1 year?

"... is listed under the National Pest Plant Accord and cannot be sold,  propagated or distributed... most Regional Pest Management Plans require  all or some landowners and/or occupiers to remove moth plant from their  property"Got it. Why do the beetles need to be introduced?

The @predicct study is designed to be v straightforward for patients and clinical teams. Patients self report inactive #IBD. We then classify clinical vs deep remission based on symptom score and CRP and faecal calprotectin (FC). https://t.co/K3w0d0qVy0

So I conceived the @predicct study thanks to generous funding from @CSO_Scotland & @CrohnsColitisC3 & others. Keep following to see what is involved. You will see that 4 out of 5 primary objectives were resting dietary variables. This was in response to what patients were asking. https://t.co/uGXfGjAiWh

So I was thinking... what if the triggers for disease flare in IBD were the same as those for disease onset. If we studied patients in remission and followed to flare this might tell us a LOT about how the environment and the microbiome affects IBD. https://t.co/8pOFP1n2cx

The course of #IBD is highly variable over time. And we have really v limited ability to predict outcomes. We are also desperately short of good quality population based longitudinal studies like the IBSEN cohort from Norway. https://t.co/aGPwa2zfae

And a western diet does appear to be critical. SO many changes compared with our human (and indeed primate) ancestors. Food processing, excess animal protein, decreased plant fibres and food additives/ emulsifiers may be important. https://t.co/vFtIkzH7qV

When it comes to the environment we can look to many studies claiming associations with many different factors  ... they can't and won't all be true. But there is a clear signal with urbanisation. https://t.co/NiIjTjFzCp

Studies of the gut microbiome in #IBD identify a clear dysbiosis. However, the issue of causality is a massive problem ... virtually all studies have been of people already with IBD so we do not know what changes are the result of inflammation (and drug treatments). https://t.co/CF3ax8rcI7

#IBD is a complex genetic condition... we have identified over 260 independent susceptibility loci for Crohn's and UC. This has taught us a lot about disease biology and is identifying druggable targets. But to date genetics tells us precious little about disease outcomes. https://t.co/HpxQacFeGZ

As I was about leaving, she whispered "I broke up with my boyfriend", I attempted to draw her back to question her further but she ran straight through the gate with heavy smile.Wow, to her she has found who she wanted but within me, I was just playing around.

She was actually surprised, we met again, spent more hours together, still I was telling her what she wanted...only that. Few days later, she called me crying heavily, I rushed straight to where she was, didn't bother to ask her anything, I only wiped away her tears.

It was already past 8PM, I didn't pick and never called back. She was the first to call me the following day,  worried over why I didn't pick her calls and never returned as well, I told her it was against my principles to make calls anytime after insha prayer (8PM)...Lies

We didn't read up to first 15 pages before we began discussing about each other & knowing what she was going through, I only said things in that regard. After about 2hrs together, I had to go & saw her off to her dormitory. As my neighbors were welcoming me, her calls too joined.

I wasn't wrong at the end, as she murmured see size now. After which I suggested we read it together, luckily she didn't mind, and as for me I have concluded my business in the library for the day, so it was a win-win situation.

Some days later, I saw her loitering around the novel section in the library, somehow confused on what to read, and being aware of her predicament, I suggested she pick up Why Good People Can't Leave Bad Relationships, she was reluctant, it must have been the size I presumed.
But because I was aware of her predicament and what she was going through, I knew what she wanted; a comforting chest, a listening ear and most especially a loving heart (whether real or not).

I waited for some more minutes to pick the lady's face and trust my photographic memory, after seeing her fully, I was certain I could pick her even in the night.1) I already knew her relationship wasn't in the best of mood 2) I was lonely & need I say I had no plans for her
